Document Readability

Something that I really didnât pay attention to before was the readability of my code. It is something that is very important for when you share your code with other people. It is important to keep this in mind because once we graduate we will work in some team for some company and collaboration will always be a part of our professional lives as Computer or Data Scientists.

For example, my Lab 4 - Question 6 code below:

california |>
  select(Date, AveragePrice, type, region) |> # select only necessary
  pivot_wider(names_from = type, # Get conventional and organic avg price on the same line
              values_from = AveragePrice) |>
  mutate(diff = abs(conventional - organic)) |> # Calculate the difference
  group_by(region) |> # group by region and not date
  summarize(`mean diff` = mean(diff)) # calculate mean of difference

Iâve employed appropriate new lines, and commented any relevant code so that anybody who reads this knows whats going on.

Document readability also includes how to format your document so that it looks professional outside of just the code chunks. Using headers, knitr tables, YAML options, and libraries like KableExtra, Knitr, and such are goods ways to format your document so that, when rendered, it is presentable. There are stereotypes that engineers canât communicate correctly or effectively, so hopefully the people who took this class will break this stereotype!

This I think is the biggest takeaway from this class. We worked with so many different data sets and performed different analysis on this data which included cleaning the data, transforming it, plotting, explaining any results or coming up with a conclusion. Not many classes give you this opportunity, but it helps develop a sense of how to process data and think about the whyâs to any patterns or relationships that you can visualize through plots or other visuals.

This combination increases your problem solving skills which I think is the best thing you can take out of a class like this.
